":"Coberley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1520–3 May 1557":"1520–3 mei 1557","1520–1557":"1520–1557","–1559":"–1559","1530–Female":"1530–Overleden","1519–1541":"1519–1541","1541–1593":"1541–1593","1554–Male":"1554–Overleden","1470–1538":"1470–1538","1474–1534":"1474–1534","JUN 1541":"juni 1541","24 JUL 1541":"24 juli 1541","1593":"1593","1470":"1470","1557":"1557","1534":"1534","3 May 1557":"3 mei 1557","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1541":"1541","1530":"1530","1474":"1474","about 1554":"circa 1554","1519":"1519","28 Jul 1538":"28 juli 1538","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1559":"1559","of England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England":"Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coberley, Gloucestershire, England":"Coberley, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alvingham, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1520–3 May 1557":"1520–3 May 1557","1520–1557":"1520–1557","–1559":"–1559","1530–Female":"1530–Deceased","1519–1541":"1519–1541","1541–1593":"1541–1593","1554–Male":"1554–Deceased","1470–1538":"1470–1538","1474–1534":"1474–1534","JUN 1541":"June 1541","24 JUL 1541":"24 July 1541","1593":"1593","1470":"1470","1557":"1557","1534":"1534","3 May 1557":"3 May 1557","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1541":"1541","1530":"1530","1474":"1474","about 1554":"about 1554","1519":"1519","28 Jul 1538":"28 July 1538","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1559":"1559","of England":"England, United Kingdom","Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England":"Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Coberley, Gloucestershire, England":"Coberley, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gooch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Goche</i> (also found as <i>Joche</i>). It was current in East Anglia from the early 12th to the early 13th centuries as a variant of Anglo-Norman French <i>Go(s)ce</i>, <i>Jo(s)ce</i>, a pet form of Old French <i>Goscelin</i>.","English: alternatively, a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>gouge</i> (from Latin <i>gobio</i>), the nominative form of Old French <i>goujon</i> (from Latin <i>gobionem</i>) ‘gudgeon’, perhaps for a gullible person.","Welsh: in southwestern England, possibly an Anglicized form of Welsh <i>coch</i>, <i>goch</i> ‘red(-haired)’, though the sound change is irregular. Compare   Gough  . It may also be a variant of Cornish and Welsh   Couch  , with the same meaning."],"variants":[{"name":"Gough","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>coch</i>, <i>goch</i> ‘red(-haired)’. The mutated form <i>goch</i> is normal after a personal name. In England, where the surname occurs from Welsh migration, it may have become hereditary in medieval times but this development was probably much later in Wales. Compare   Gooch   and   Couch  , which may sometimes derive from the same source.","English: variant of   Goff  .","Irish (especially Waterford and Dublin): shortened form of   McGough  ."]},{"name":"Gouge","meanings":["English: variant of   Gooch   or   Couch  ."]},{"name":"Googe","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire and Lincolnshire): variant of   Gooch  ."]},{"name":"Couch","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): nickname from Middle English <i>couch(e)</i> ‘hump, hunch’, used for a hunchback. In Cornwall and Devon it is usually pronounced as <i>Cooch</i>.","English (Cornwall and Devon): variant of   Gooch  .","English (Cornwall and Devon): from Middle English <i>coche</i>, <i>couche</i> ‘bed, couch, tablecloth’ (Old French <i>couche</i>, <i>culche</i>). It could have been a metonymic occupational name for someone who made such items or a nickname for a lazy individual. Alternatively, it could have been applied to someone who produced <i>couchwork</i>, a luxurious embroidery in which gold or silver thread and jewels were sewn into satin or silk robes."]},{"name":"Gotch","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>coch</i>, <i>goch</i> ‘red(-haired)’; see   Gooch   3.","English (Northamptonshire): variant of   Gooch   1 and 2.","Americanized form of German <b>Götsch</b> (see   Gotsch  )."]},{"name":"Gouch","meanings":["English: variant of   Gooch  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Gooch was born in 1520, in Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England, his father, John Gooche, was 50 and his mother, Jane Bridges, was 46. He married Ellen Gadbury in 1552. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 3 May 1557, in his hometown, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1520–3 May 1557":"1520–3. mai 1557","1520–1557":"1520–1557","–1559":"–1559","1530–Female":"1530–Surnud","1519–1541":"1519–1541","1541–1593":"1541–1593","1554–Male":"1554–Surnud","1470–1538":"1470–1538","1474–1534":"1474–1534","JUN 1541":"juuni 1541","24 JUL 1541":"24. juuli 1541","1593":"1593","1470":"1470","1557":"1557","1534":"1534","3 May 1557":"3. mai 1557","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1541":"1541","1530":"1530","1474":"1474","about 1554":"umbes 1554","1519":"1519","28 Jul 1538":"28. juuli 1538","1549":"1549","1538":"1538","1559":"1559","of England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England":"Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coberley, Gloucestershire, England":"Coberley, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Alvingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Alvingham, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1520–3 May 1557":"1520–3. toukokuuta 1557","1520–1557":"1520–1557","–1559":"–1559","1530–Female":"1530–Kuollut","1519–1541":"1519–1541","1541–1593":"1541–1593","1554–Male":"1554–Kuollut","1470–1538":"1470–1538","1474–1534":"1474–1534","JUN 1541":"kesäkuu 1541","24 JUL 1541":"24. heinäkuuta 1541","1593":"1593","1470":"1470","1557":"1557","1534":"1534","3 May 1557":"3. toukokuuta 1557","1554":"1554","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1541":"1541","1530":